<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
  Hardened-runtime entitlements for the Electron app (required for notarization).
  Credentials are encrypted with Electron safeStorage, which uses the app's own
  keychain-stored key via Chromium os_crypt — that path needs NO
  keychain-access-groups entitlement (that entitlement is only for shared
  access groups), so none is declared.

  Deliberately minimal: allow-jit alone, because every additional entitlement here
  weakens the hardened runtime for the whole app process.

  Two entitlements were removed and must NOT be re-added without recording the
  module that forced them:

  - allow-unsigned-executable-memory: redundant alongside allow-jit on current
    Electron, which uses the MAP_JIT path that allow-jit covers.
  - disable-library-validation: the broadest of the three — it lets ANY unsigned
    dylib load into the app process. It exists for native modules, but node-pty
    ships prebuilt .node binaries that electron-builder signs with this app's own
    identity, so library validation should accept them.

  If a packaged build fails to launch, or the terminal panel goes dead (node-pty
  failing to load is the expected symptom), re-add the ONE entitlement that fixes
  it and note here which module needed it.
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
  <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-jit</key>
  <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
